{"id":14881858,"mediaExerciseId":"b0d940e5-690b-4dca-860f-1f5eb33fa3b0","exerciseName":"1","chapterName":"24","chapterTitle":"Options and Corporate Finance","groupId":612498,"groupTitle":"Critical Thinking Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":822,"solutions":[{"id":5999816,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this problem, we will learn about the call option and put option.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"### Define call option.\n\n**Call Option** is a contract that gives a holder the right to buy a stock.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"### Define put option.\n\n**Put Option** is a contract that gives a holder the right but not the obligation to sell a stock.\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":103,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/4c81762533b01fca1890f4536ca7908c/9ea1c9f6c68f4ea2fc8f62c3f8789f34/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":53,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/4c81762533b01fca1890f4536ca7908c/9ea1c9f6c68f4ea2fc8f62c3f8789f34/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"### Under what circumstances might you want to buy each.\n\n**Call Option** can be bought if an investor believes the price of a security is likely to rise as they will benefit from the price hike. Also, the investorâ€™s total risk is only limited to the premium paid for the option.\n\n**Put Option** can be bought if an investor believes that certain stocks in his or her portfolio may drop in price but do not want to abandon his or her long-term position. If the stock price declines, then profits from put options will offset losses to the actual stock.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"### Which one has a greater potential profit.\n\n**Call option** has greater potential profit because an investor can own an underlying stock while at the same time writing a call option. They will collect the option premium and hope the option expires below the strike price, which will generate additional income as an investor.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"df41283b-753b-4e14-b638-0d0c0d467d49","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":5}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14881859,"exerciseName":"2","page":822,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"374323e0-5d56-442e-a66c-51448f732916","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-24-critical-thinking-questions-2-374323e0-5d56-442e-a66c-51448f732916"},{"id":14881860,"exerciseName":"3","page":822,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"0af4f1c5-baac-4801-847f-231331d99833","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/ch